            <biogHist>
                <p>Christina, also known as Christy, Curstina, or Christian, was born to Alexander
                    MacNeil (born c. 1761), crofter, and Margaret n√©e MacDonald (born c. 1771). The
                    1841 Census records her living with her parents and elder sister, Elizabeth
                    (born c. 1816) at Brevig on Barra. By the 1851 Census Christina had married
                    Roderick MacDonald and had had two children, John and Alexander, aged 3 and 2
                    respectfully. The family resided in Earsary and Roderick was a crofter with 21
                    acres of land. Ten years later, still living in Earsary, a further two children
                    had been born, James and Mary, aged 8 and 4, with James attending school. The
                    1871 Census still has them living in Earsary, but with only their daughter Mary
                    at home at the time. In 1881 they are still in Earsary in a house with three
                    rooms with windows and James and Mary are living with them. On the 25 January
                    1887, Christina's husband Roderick died of old age with the death certificate
                    being signed by his daughter Mary. In 1891 Christina was living with her
                    daughter, a domestic servant, in a smaller house as it only has two rooms with
                    windows. </p>
                <p>Christina died in August 1895 at 5pm also of old age, with her daughter Mary
                    signing the death certificate. There was no medical attendant present.</p>
                <p>Carmichael met Christina in 1885 and she gave a song entitled 'Thig A Mhoire
                    Mhios Na Bo'.</p>
